n Idea of Tragic Form -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeyond the Fifth Century brings together 13 scholars from various disciplines (Classics, Ancient History, Mediaeval Studies) to explore interactions with Greek tragedy from the 4th century BCE up to the Middle Ages. The volume breaks new ground in several ways. Its chronological scope encompasses periods that are not usually part of research on tragedy reception, especially the Hellenistic period, late antiquity and the Middle Ages. The volume also considers not just performance reception but various other modes of reception, between different literary genres and media (inscriptions, vase paintings, recording technology). There is a pervasive interest in interactions between tragedy and society-at-large, such as festival culture and entertainment (both public and private), education, religious practice, even life-style. Finally, the volume features studies of a comparative nature which focus less on genealogical connections (although such may be present) but rather on the study of equivalences.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aClassical literaturexGreek influences. 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)xAppreciationxHistory. 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aIntertextuality. 0aLiterature, MedievalxGreek influences. 4aRezeption. 4aTragödie (Antike). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Tragedy.  aReception.1 aBaertschi, Annette M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCeccarelli, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGildenhard, Ingo, econtributor.4ct